<p><strong>ETA:</strong> Since I got downvoted, maybe I wasn't being clear. I think that the Warren Buffett quote applies to human psychology more than to game theory in general. If outright deception were easy, it would probably become a <em>good</em> strategy to keep your allies in some doubt about your intentions, as a bargaining chip. But we humans don't seem to be good at pulling that off, and so ambivalence is a strong signal of opposition.</p></div></div><div style="display: none;" id="edit_body_t1_2xca"></div><div class="comment-links"><ul class="clear"><li class="first"><a id="up_t1_2xca" class="up" onclick="showcover(true, 'vote_t1_2xca')" >Vote up</a></li><li><a id="down_t1_2xca" class="down" onclick="showcover(true, 'vote_t1_2xca')" >Vote down</a></li><li><a id="permalink_t1_2xca" href="http://lesswrong.com/lw/30k/rationality_quotes_november_2010/2xca?c=1" class=" " target="_parent" >Permalink</a></li><li><a id="parent_t1_2xca" href="#2wyg" class="bylink">Parent</a></li><li><a id="reply_a_t1_2xca" class="" href="javascript:reply('t1_2xca')">Reply</a></li></ul><span id=status_t1_2xca class="error" style="display: none;"></span></div></div></div><div id="child_t1_2xca" class="child" ><div id="siteTable_t1_2xca" class="sitetable"><div id="ajaxHook_t1_2xca" class="ajaxhook"></div><div id="thingrow_t1_2xci" class="comment" ><div id="pre_t1_2xci" class="parent"><a name="2xci" ></a></div><div id="entry_t1_2xci" class="entry"><div id="collapsed_t1_2xci" class="comment-meta collapsed clear " style='display:none'><span class="comment-author"><strong><span class="author gray"><a id="author_t1_2xci" href="http://lesswrong.com/user/Perplexed/">Perplexed</a></span></strong></span><span class="comment-date">09 November 2010 01:43:45AM</span><span class="votes " >0 points</span><script type="text/javascript">vl['t1_2xci'] = ['-1 points', '0 points', '1 point' ];</script>&#32;<a href="#" class="expand" onclick="return showcomment('t1_2xci')">[+] (85 children)</a></div><d