lasBarta/">SilasBarta</a></span></strong></span><span class="comment-date">23 November 2010 11:03:52PM</span><span class="votes " id='score_t1_2ztv'>0 points</span><script type="text/javascript">vl['t1_2ztv'] = ['-1 points', '0 points', '1 point' ];</script>&#32;<a href="#" class="expand" onclick="return hidecomment('t1_2ztv')">[-]</a></div><div id="body_t1_2ztv" class="comment-content"><div class="md"><p>And a cat is a device for turning kibble into cuddle.</p></div></div><div style="display: none;" id="edit_body_t1_2ztv"></div><div class="comment-links"><ul class="clear"><li class="first"><a id="up_t1_2ztv" class="up" onclick="showcover(true, 'vote_t1_2ztv')" >Vote up</a></li><li><a id="down_t1_2ztv" class="down" onclick="showcover(true, 'vote_t1_2ztv')" >Vote down</a></li><li><a id="permalink_t1_2ztv" href="http://lesswrong.com/lw/30k/rationality_quotes_november_2010/2ztv?c=1" class=" " target="_parent" >Permalink</a></li><li><a id="parent_t1_2ztv" href="#2x40" class="bylink">Parent</a></li><li><a id="reply_a_t1_2ztv" class="" href="javascript:reply('t1_2ztv')">Reply</a></li></ul><span id=status_t1_2ztv class="error" style="display: none;"></span></div></div></div><div id="child_t1_2ztv" class="child" ></div><div class="clearleft"><!--IE6sux--></div></div><div class="clearleft"><!--IE6sux--></div></div></div><div class="clearleft"><!--IE6sux--></div></div><div class="clearleft"><!--IE6sux--></div></div></div><div class="clearleft"><!--IE6sux--></div></div><div class="clearleft"><!--IE6sux--></div><div id="thingrow_t1_2wik" class="comment" ><div id="pre_t1_2wik" class="parent"><a name="2wik" ></a></div><div id="entry_t1_2wik" class="entry"><div id="collapsed_t1_2wik" class="comment-meta collapsed clear " style='display:none'><span class="comment-author"><strong><span class="author gray"><a id="author_t1_2wik" href="http://lesswrong.com/user/MichaelGR/">MichaelGR</a></span></strong></span><span class="comment-date">04 November 2010 09:10:40PM</span><span class="votes " >12 points</span><script type="text/javascript">vl['t1_2wik'] = ['11 points', '12 points', '13 points' ];</script>&#32;<a href="#" class="expand" onclick="return showcomment('t1_2wik')">[+] (6 children)</a></div><div id="display_t1_2wik" class="" ><div class="comment-meta clear"><span class="comment-author"><strong><span class="author"><a id="author_t1_2wik" href="http://lesswrong.com/user/MichaelGR/">MichaelGR</a></span></strong></span><span class="comment-date">04 November 2010 09:10:40PM</span><span class="votes " id='score_t1_2wik'>12 points</span><script type="text/javascript">vl['t1_2wik'] = ['11 points', '12 points', '13 points' ];</script>&#32;<a href="#" class="expand" onclick="return hidecomment('t1_2wik')">[-]</a></div><div id="body_t1_2wik" class="comment-content"><div class="md"><p>It is a profound and necessary truth that the deep things in science are not found because they are useful, they are found because it was possible to find them. -J. Robert Oppenheimer.</p></div></div><div style="display: none;" id="edit_body_t1_2wik"></div><div class="comment-links"><ul class="clear"><li class="first"><a id="up_t1_2wik" class="up" onclick="showcover(true, 'vote_t1_2wik')" >Vote up</a></li><li><a id="down_t1_2wik" class="down" onclick="showcover(true, 'vote_t1_2wik')" >Vote down</a></li><li><a id="permalink_t1_2wik" href="http://lesswrong.com/lw/30k/rationality_quotes_november_2010/2wik?c=1" class=" " target="_parent" >Permalink</a></li><li><a id="reply_a_t1_2wik" class="" href="javascript:reply('t1_2wik')">Reply</a></li></ul><span id=status_t1_2wik class="error" style="display: none;"></span></div></div></div><div id="child_t1_2wik" class="child" ><div id="siteTable_t1_2wik" class="sitetable"><div id="ajaxHook_t1_2wik" class="ajaxhook"></div><div id="thingrow_t1_2wka" class="comment" ><div id="pre_t1_2wka" class="parent"><a name="2wka" ></a></div><div id="entry_t1_2wka" class="entry"><div id="collapsed_t1_2wka" class="comment-meta collapsed clear " style='display:none'><span class="comment-author"><strong><span class="author gray"><a id="author_t1_2wka" href="http://lesswrong.com/user/bentarm/">bentarm</a></span></strong></span><span class="comment-date">04 November 2010 10:56:05PM</span><span class="votes " >2 points</span><script type="text/javascript">vl['t1_2wka'] = ['1 point', '2 points', '3 points' ];</script>&#32;<a href="#" class="expand" onclick="return showcomment('t1_2wka')">[+] (4 children)</a></div><div id="display_t1_2wka" class="" ><div class="comment-meta clear"><span class="comment-author"><strong><span class="author"><a id="author_t1_2wka" href="http://lesswrong.com/user/bentarm/">bentarm</a></span></strong></span><span class="comment-date">04 November 2010 10:56:05PM</span><span class="votes " id='score_t1_2wka'>2 points</span><script type="text/javascript">vl['t1_2wka'] = ['1 point', '2 points', '3 points' ];</script>&#32;<a href="#" class="expand" onclick="return hidecomment('t1_2wka')">[-]</a></div><div id="body_t1_2wka" class="comment-content"><div class="md"><p>There are two quite different interpretations of this quote: it either says something about scientists, or something about scientific truths, and I'm not sure which is the intention.</p>

<p>The two messages I see are:</p>

<ol>
<li><p>Scientists just <em>enjoy</em> seeking truths, you don't need to give them the incentive of practical applications in order for them to do science, so any truths that can be discovered will be, regardless of their usefulness.</p></li>
<li><p>There are an awful lot of true things. The ones that we know might not be the most useful, but they are the ones that happen to lie in the (extremely small?) subset of true things that humans are capable of understanding.</p></li>
</ol>

<p>To an extent, I guess both of these are true... which one was Oppenheimer aiming at?</p></div></div><div style="display: none;" id="edit_body_t1_2wka"></div><div class="comment-links"><ul class="clear"><li class="first"><a id="up_t1_2wka" class="up" onclick="showcover(true, 'vote_t1_2wka')" >Vote up</a></li><li><a id="down_t1_2wka" class="down" onclick="showcover(true, 'vote_t1_2wka')" >Vote down</a></li><li><a id="permalink_t1_2wka" href="http://lesswrong.com/lw/30k/rationality_quotes_november_2010/2wka?c=1" class=" " target="_parent" >Permalink</a></li><li><a id="parent_t1_2wka" href="#2wik" class="bylink">Parent</a></li><li><a id="reply_a_t1_2wka" class="" href="javascript:reply('t1_2wka')">Reply</a></li></ul><span id=status_t1_2wka class="error" style="display: none;"></span></div></div></div><div id="child_t1_2wka" class="child" ><div id="siteTable_t1_2wka" class="sitetable"><div id="ajaxHook_t1_2wka" class="ajaxhook"></div><div id="thingrow_t1_2wtw" class="comment" ><div id="pre_t1_2wtw" class="parent"><a name="2wtw" ></a></div><div id="entry_t1_2wtw" class="entry"><div id="collapsed_t1_2wtw" class="comment-meta collapsed clear " style='display:none'><span class="comment-author"><strong><span class="author gray"><a id="author_t1_2wtw" href="http://lesswrong.com/user/Perplexed/">Perplexed</a></span></strong></span><span class="comment-date">05 November 2010 10:54:44PM</span><span class="votes " >1 point</span><script type="text/javascript">vl['t1_2wtw'] = ['0 points', '1 point', '2 points' ];</script>&#32;<a href="#" class="expand" onclick="return showcomment('t1_2wtw')">[+] (0 children)</a></div><div id="display_t1_2wtw" class="" ><div class="comment-meta clear"><span class="comment-author"><strong><span class="author"><a id="author_t1_2wtw" href="http://lesswrong.com/user/Perplexed/">Perplexed</a></span></strong></span><span class="comment-date">05 November 2010 10:54:44PM</span><span class="votes " id='score_t1_2wtw'>1 point</span><script type="text/javascript">vl['t1_2wtw'] = ['0 points', '1 point', '2 points' ];</script>&#32;<a href="#" class="expand" onclick="return hidecomment('t1_2wtw')">[-]</a></div><div id="body_t1_2wtw" class="comment-content"><div class="md"><blockquote>
  <p>[one interpretation of Oppenheimer:]  There are an awful lot of true things. The ones that we know might not be the most useful, but they are the ones that happen to lie in the (extremely small?) subset of true things that humans are capable of understanding.</p>
</blockquote>

<p>Quibble: Two things you might have missed:</p>

<ul>
<li>Oppenheimer was talking about "deep things in science", not about "truths."</li>
<li>He said "possible to find them", not "possible to understand them".</li>
